<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,151,947]" box="[151,1162,301,326]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
DISTRIBUTION. S 
<collectingCountry box="[348,474,301,326]" name="Azerbaijan" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Azerbaijan</collectingCountry>
, most of 
<collectingCountry box="[577,625,302,325]" name="Iran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Iran</collectingCountry>
, S 
<collectingCountry box="[658,817,301,326]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[828,968,301,326]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
, and W 
<collectingCountry box="[1060,1159,301,326]" name="Pakistan" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,151,947]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
DISTRIBUTION IN 
<collectingCountry box="[354,411,339,362]" name="Iran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">IRAN</collectingCountry>
. 
<figureCitation box="[428,527,338,363]" captionStart="FIGURES 98–103. 98" captionStartId="88.[151,264,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,213,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-53@88.[151,1436,193,1536]" captionTargetPageId="88" captionText="FIGURES 98–103. 98. Eremias lineolata. 99. Eremias montana. 100. Eremias nigrocellata. 101. Eremias nova. 102. Eremias papenfussi. 103. Eremias persica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929754/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
. The whole central plateau south of the 
<collectingRegion box="[995,1073,338,363]" country="Iran" name="Alborz" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Alborz</collectingRegion>
Mts. and including the Zagros. There are no records from the central desert systems Dasht-e Lut and Dasht-e Kavir which are apparently avoided by this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,151,947]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">HABITAT. Open plains and slopes with sparse grassy vegetation, usually associated with gravel surfaces but can be found also on mixed sand and gravel or silt and gravel.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,151,947]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
REMARKS. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[279,464,526,549]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[279,464,526,549]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Eremias persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is formed by five geographically isolated clades in 
<collectingCountry box="[1068,1113,526,549]" name="Iran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Iran</collectingCountry>
that diverged consecutively 6–10 Mya, which corresponds with the uplift and subsequent aridization of the Iranian plateau (
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, E. &amp; Rastegar-Pouyani, N. &amp; Noureini, S. K. &amp; Joger, U. &amp; Wink, M." pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="641 - 660" refId="ref63589" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, E., Rastegar-Pouyani, N., Noureini, S. K., Joger, U. &amp; Wink, M. (2010 b) Molecular phylogeny of the Eremias persica complex of the Iranian plateau (Reptilia: Lacertidae), based on mtDNA sequences. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 158, 641 - 660. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2009.00553. x" type="journal article" year="2010">
Rastegar-Pouyani 
<emphasis box="[151,207,597,622]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
2010b
</bibRefCitation>
). The basal lineage of the radiation contains a central Zagros population of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[1135,1248,598,621]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[1135,1248,598,621]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E. persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
together with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rastegar-Pouyani &amp; Rastegar-Pouyani" authorityYear="2001" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and an unnamed form from NW 
<collectingCountry box="[657,702,634,657]" name="Iran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Iran</collectingCountry>
thus rendering 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[891,1010,634,657]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[891,1010,634,657]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E. persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
paraphyletic. 
<taxonomicName authority="Rastegar-Pouyani &amp; Nilson" authorityName="Rastegar-Pouyani &amp; Nilson" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigrolateralis">
<emphasis box="[1179,1436,633,658]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Eremias nigrolateralis</emphasis>
Rastegar-Pouyani &amp; Nilson
</taxonomicName>
, a species described principally on the basis of dorsal colour pattern differences, was found to be nested within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[456,573,706,729]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[456,573,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E. persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and was synonymized with it (
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, E. &amp; Rastegar-Pouyani, N. &amp; Noureini, S. K. &amp; Joger, U. &amp; Wink, M." box="[937,1290,705,730]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="641 - 660" refId="ref63589" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, E., Rastegar-Pouyani, N., Noureini, S. K., Joger, U. &amp; Wink, M. (2010 b) Molecular phylogeny of the Eremias persica complex of the Iranian plateau (Reptilia: Lacertidae), based on mtDNA sequences. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 158, 641 - 660. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2009.00553. x" type="journal article" year="2010">
Rastegar-Pouyani 
<emphasis box="[1148,1207,705,730]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
2010b
</bibRefCitation>
). In order to settle the taxonomy of this species complex the authors propose to raise four 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blanford" authorityYear="1874" box="[1048,1165,742,765]" class="Reptilia" family="Lacertidae" genus="Eremias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[1048,1165,742,765]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">E. persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clades (from the Zabol area, central Zagros, 
<collectingRegion box="[398,475,777,802]" country="Iran" name="Tehran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Tehran</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[538,619,777,802]" country="Iran" name="Qazvin" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Qazvin</collectingRegion>
area, and 
<collectingRegion box="[745,902,777,802]" country="Iran" name="Ardabil" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Ardabil Prov.</collectingRegion>
) to species ranks and two (from the southern Zagros and 
<collectingRegion box="[290,460,813,838]" country="Iran" name="Golestan" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Golestan Prov.</collectingRegion>
) to subspecies ranks. The population from the central Zagros may be similar to the undescribed species mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Frynta, D. &amp; Moravec, J. &amp; Cihakova, J. &amp; Sadlo, J. &amp; Hodkova, Z. &amp; Kaftan, M. &amp; Kodym, P. &amp; Kral, D. &amp; Pitule, V. &amp; Sejna, L." box="[541,762,849,874]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="3 - 17" refId="ref50917" refString="Frynta, D., Moravec, J., Cihakova, J., Sadlo, J., Hodkova, Z., Kaftan, M., Kodym, P., Kral, D., Pitule, V. &amp; Sejna, L. (1997) Results of the Czech Biological Expedition to Iran. Part 1. Notes on the distribution of amphibians and reptiles. Acta Societatis Zoologicae Bohemicae, 61, 3 - 17." type="journal article" year="1997">
Frynta 
<emphasis box="[621,677,849,874]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
(1997)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
